HEADWORD: Recidivism
<hw>Re*cid"i*vism</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*s⟦icr⟧d"⟦icr⟧*v⟦icr⟧z'm)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being recidivous;
relapse,</def> <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Criminology)</fld>, <def>a
falling back or relapse into prior criminal habits, esp. after
conviction and punishment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The old English system of recognizances, in which the guilty party
deposits a sum of money, is an excellent guarantee to society against
<qex>recidivism</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Havelock Ellis.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recidivist</ent>⟦br⟧
